03804nam a22006015i 9780823291700DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232917007 a10.1515/97808232917002doi  a(DE-B1597)566076  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041702bisacsh1 aGosetti-Ferencei, Jennifer Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHeidegger, Hölderlin, and the Subject of Poetic Language :bToward a New Poetics of Dasein /cJennifer Anna Gosetti-Ferencei. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations of Frequently Cited Works -- tIntroduction: The Dialogue Between Poetry and Thinking -- t1 Heidegger's Critique of Subjectivity and the Poetic Tum -- t2 Heidegger's Holderlin: Andenken and Ereiguis Beyond Subjectivity -- t3 Poetic Subjectivity and the Elusiveness of Being -- t4 The Critique of Technology and the Poetics of "Life" -- t5 The Politics of Sacrifice: The Sublime and the Caesura -- t6 Revolutionary Poetics and the Subject-in-Process -- t7 A New Poetics of Dasein -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHeidegger's interpretations of the poetry of Hölderlin are central to Heidegger's later philosophy and have determined the mainstream reception of Hölderlin's poetry. Gosetti-Ferencei argues that Heidegger has overlooked central elements in Hölderlin's poetics, such as a Kantian understanding of aesthetic subjectivity and a commitment to Enlightenment ideals. These elements, she argues, resist the more politically distressing aspects of Heidegger's interpretations, including Heidegger's nationalist valorization of the German language and sense of nationhood, or Heimat. In the context of Hölderlin's poetics of alienation, exile, and wandering, Gosetti-Ferencei draws a different model of poetic subjectivity, which engages Heidegger's later philosophy of Gelassenheit, calmness, or letting be. In so doing, she is able to pose a phenomenologically sensitive theory of poetic language and a "new poetics of Dasein," or being there.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291700/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK